# Supabase migration best practices

Use this when writing or modifying migrations in `supabase/migrations/` or when `supabase db push` fails.

## 1. Idempotent policies and triggers

**Rule:** For new migrations that add RLS policies or triggers, always use `DROP ... IF EXISTS` before `CREATE POLICY` / `CREATE TRIGGER`. That way re-runs and partial applies (e.g. after a failed push or when the object already exists on remote) do not fail.

### Policies

```sql
DROP POLICY IF EXISTS "Policy name" ON table_name;
CREATE POLICY "Policy name"
  ON table_name FOR SELECT
  USING (...);
```

### Triggers

```sql
DROP TRIGGER IF EXISTS trigger_name ON table_name;
CREATE TRIGGER trigger_name
  BEFORE UPDATE ON table_name
  FOR EACH ROW
  EXECUTE FUNCTION some_function();
```

### Why

- Migrations may be applied more than once (retry after partial failure, or remote already has the object from dashboard/another branch).
- Plain `CREATE POLICY` / `CREATE TRIGGER` then errors with "already exists".
- `DROP ... IF EXISTS` then `CREATE` makes the migration safe to re-run.

## 2. "Local migration files to be inserted before" (history repair)

**Symptom:** `supabase db push` fails with a message like:

```text
Found local migration files to be inserted before the last migration on remote database.
Rerun the command with --include-all flag to apply these migrations:
supabase/migrations/20250101000000_initial_schema.sql
supabase/migrations/20250109_add_source_files.sql
```

**Cause:** The remote database’s migration history is missing one or more entries that exist locally (e.g. remote was set up without those files, or history was applied in a different order).

**Fix (when the remote already has that schema):** Mark the missing migrations as applied **without** running their SQL:

```bash
supabase migration repair <version> --status applied
```

- `<version>` is the migration name without `.sql`, e.g. `20250101000000` or `20250109`.
- Run once per missing migration (oldest first if multiple).
- Then run `supabase db push` again.

**When to use:** Only when you are sure the remote database already contains the schema/objects from that migration (e.g. it was applied manually or via another path). Do **not** use `--status applied` for a migration whose SQL has never been applied on the remote; that would record it as applied while leaving the schema unchanged.

**Check status:** `supabase migration list` shows which migrations are applied locally vs on the remote.

## 3a. PostgreSQL gotcha: `round()` and float8

`similarity()` / `word_similarity()` (pg_trgm) return **double precision**. PostgreSQL **does not** define `round(double precision, integer)` — only `round(numeric, int)`. Use an explicit cast before the second argument:

```sql
ROUND((GREATEST(...) * 100)::numeric, 0)
```

Otherwise RPCs fail with **42883** (`function round(double precision, integer) does not exist`).

## 3b. Heavy `pg_trgm` RPCs (statement timeout 57014)

Calling `similarity()` / `word_similarity()` for **every row** without index-friendly filters can hit **statement timeout** on hosted Postgres (e.g. Supabase REST).

- Prefer **`%`** (similarity vs `pg_trgm.similarity_threshold`) and **`<%`** (word similarity vs `pg_trgm.word_similarity_threshold`) in `WHERE`, with `SET LOCAL` / `set_config(..., true)` for session thresholds.
- Add **`GIN` index** on search columns, e.g. `USING gin (lower(title) gin_trgm_ops)` on reference tables.
- See `search_onet_occupations` in migrations `20260323160000` / `20260323170000`.

## 3. Branches, shared demos, and live databases

**Never** change the SQL inside a migration file **after** it has been applied to a shared remote (demo, staging, production). Supabase records the version as applied; editing the file locally can cause checksum drift in CI, or teammates will think the remote ran different SQL than the repo.

**When you need a fix:** add a **new** file under `supabase/migrations/` with a **new timestamp** after the latest remote migration (e.g. `20260323150000_fix_....sql`). Use `DROP ... IF EXISTS` / `DROP FUNCTION ... CASCADE` when replacing functions so the new migration is idempotent.

**If a bad migration already shipped:** keep the old file as-is in git history; ship a follow-up migration that corrects the database. It is OK for two migrations to end up defining the same function (second one wins); that is normal for hotfixes.

**Demo branch / prospect accounts:** merging `main` into `demo` and running `supabase db push` (or your deploy pipeline) applies only **new** migrations. Do not delete migration files that were already applied remotely—`db push` will fail or history will drift.

**“Inserted before” / out-of-order history:** see section 2 above.

**Reference-only SQL:** `src/supabase/migrations/` (older paths) may be used for seed or docs; canonical applied history is **`supabase/migrations/`** only.

## 4. CLI migration version matching and `schema_migrations.version`

Use this when `supabase db push` fails with **Remote migration versions not found in local migrations directory**, or when you are tempted to fix history with raw SQL on `supabase_migrations.schema_migrations`.

### How the CLI matches files to “versions”

- Each local file must be named **`YYYYMMDDHHMMSS_description.sql`** (see CLI: skipped migrations log *file name must match pattern `<timestamp>_name.sql`*).
- The Supabase CLI aligns the remote `schema_migrations.version` column with each file using the migration **version** shown in **`supabase migration list`** (the **Local** column). That is effectively the **leading numeric timestamp** for that file (e.g. `20260330100001`), not necessarily storing the full string `20260330100001_add_preferred_language` on the remote—**depending on CLI version and how the migration was applied.**

### Rules for agents (and humans)

1. **Do not** hand-`UPDATE` `schema_migrations.version` to the full `filename_without_.sql` unless you have verified **`supabase migration list`** and **`supabase db push`** both accept it. Wrong values cause *Remote migration versions not found in local migrations directory* even when the `.sql` file exists.
2. Prefer **`supabase migration repair`** and normal **`supabase db push`** over ad-hoc edits to the history table.
3. **Lexicographic order:** Migrations apply in **string sort order** of the filename. For example, `20260330100001_foo.sql` sorts **before** `20260330_add_bar.sql` (left-to-right character comparison). Use a full timestamp prefix that sorts in the order you need (e.g. `20260330000001_add_recurrence_...` **before** `20260330100001_...`).
4. **Delete** accidental macOS duplicates such as `* 2.sql`; they are not valid migration names and confuse history.

### Check

- Run `supabase migration list` and confirm **Local** and **Remote** agree for every row before/after any repair.

